@Clark: Maybe as explanation in case this is the confusing part: The this.setState(({ autoReload }) extracts the autoReload value from the previous state. That's why we need to use autoReload: !autoReload in the next line to toggle the value and cause a state update.

The longer version for this statement would be
this.setState(prevState => {
  autoReload: !prevState.autoReload,
})

Another (shorter) version would be 

this.setState({
  autoReload: !this.state.autoReload,
})

Maybe we could switch to one of those versions which IMHO make it clearer where the autoReload value comes from.

